      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e This seems to offer some wiggle room. Who determine whether it really happens? A TOF vote? Or should we simply say \"will be removed\".\n\nThe overall intent of this document is to document \"what\" not \"how\".  I\u0027d like to keep it that way if we can just so that the \"how\" can evolve over time without needing additional process that only one or two people really need to execute on.\n\nI suspect \"can\" wiggle room is intentional by patrick, but I\u0027d be in support of either way.  I think the _MUST_ in the previous sentence is the more important one.\n\n\u003e I think there are some repos which are important but not actively developed in which it makes sense to allow a maintainer to remain, assuming they are responsive to any changes, even if they are not actively committing to OpenBMC anymore. If there is an option to not remove someone, I think we should define the process in which we do remove them so it doesn\u0027t appear arbitrary.\n\nIs there a concrete example of this?  I would assume that maintainers that are responding to changes would meet the bar for active in a 6 month period, but I agree, there\u0027s a theoretical grey area.  I don\u0027t think it\u0027s worth trying to change this commit to try to address that.",
      "parentUuid": "ccf6f124_0cb3907e",
